<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-12-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-12-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="158" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                        <head>158. Memorandum of Conversation, December 28, between <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1">Dobrynin</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HWA_1">Harriman</persName><note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d158fn1"><persName corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName>
                                acceptance of principle of on-the-ground inspections. Confidential.
                                1 p. Department of State, Central Files,
                            700.5611/12–2862.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline>
                                <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1962-12-28">December 28, 1962</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <pb facs="d158-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d158-1"/>
                        <list type="subject">
                            <head>SUBJECT</head>
                            <item>Nuclear Testing</item>
                        </list>
                        <list type="participants">
                            <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                            <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1">Dobrynin</persName>
                                <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss></item>
                            <item><persName corresp="#p_HWA_1">W. Averell Harriman</persName></item>
                        </list>
                        <p>During a conversation at dinner at the Soviet Embassy, Ambassador
                                <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1">Dobrynin</persName> expressed optimism
                            that an agreement on the ending of nuclear testing could now be reached
                            since Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName> had
                            accepted the principle of on-the-ground inspections. The difference now
                            was only how many.</p>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>